title: Batched Upserts to Pinecone
body:
Pinecone upserts are currently done via an upsert call for each embedding result. This is slower than batching upserts (which is recommended in: https://docs.pinecone.io/docs/insert-data).

As an example, for a set of 850 documents I have, batching upserts takes 6 seconds (whereas the current one-by-one upserting takes 50 seconds), so batching is much faster.

This change should lead to faster index construction/updating/adding for GPTPineconeIndex.

title: [0.5.0] Composability
body:
![composability (1)](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5567282/227745317-3ed4e09b-6879-4e48-a89b-d148616d7932.png)


### Conceptual changes
* Decouple index structure and data
> `V2IndexStruct` is no longer a `BaseDocument`. 
* We introduce `CompositeIndexStruct` to model a composed graph
> This makes `ComposableGraph` is very similar to `BaseGPTIndex`. We could unify this further later.
* Model relationship between indices via `IndexNode`
> `IndexNode` is a `Node` with a pointer to an `IndexStruct`  
> We no longer "set_text" on a `IndexStruct`, which breaks various abstractions. The same can be expressed as creating an `IndexNode` with some summary text, and point it to the `IndexStruct`.

### Storage
* We use DocumentStore to store data (i.e. `Document` and `Node`)
> This eliminates many ugly "if this is an index struct, do X, otherwise do Y" logic.
* We save `V2IndexStruct` separately
> To support saving and loading polymorphic objects, we always save its _type_ along with the actual object

### Querying
* Remove recursive logic from `BaseGPTIndexQuery`
> Now recursive logic is entirely managed via `QueryRunner`. This removes mutual recursion and make things easier to reason about.
* Introduce `def retrieve` and `def synthesize` API
> This makes it explicit which queries support recursive call vs. not.

### Noop refactor
* group common params into `ServiceContext` object
> We basically pass these around across all data objects. This is mostly an attempt to make code cleaner. 

### Todos
- [x] Figure out how to deal with query type to query map
- [x] Fix composability for tree 
- [x] Lint and tests

### Future
- [ ] Fix query combiner support.
- [ ] Update notebooks.
- [ ] Update readme. 
- [ ] Support query transformation with index struct text. 
- [ ] Clean up `BaseGPTIndexQuery` ctor mess

title: Add support for prepending messages with Chat models
body:
This has been a pretty frequently requested feature. This will support both ChatGPT and other models like davinci

I know the `ChatGPTLLMPredictor` supported this, but I think that's deprecated now right? (We should really remove it, it doesn't work at the moment... I can remove it in this PR if you want haha)

Anyways, let me know if this approach makes sense or if there's a better way. 

P.S. -- I'll fix the linting eventually, langchain types are just being silly right now.

Here's a quick demo:
```
prepend_messages = [
    SystemMessagePromptTemplate.from_template("You are the world's smartest chatbot, act like one.")
]
llm_predictor = LLMPredictor(
```

title: Fix breaking changes from Langchain update to 0.0.119
body:
Langchain is a package that is under constant change and development; breaking changes can come at any time.

I propose to lock the langchain version Llama index so that it will always be stable on any fresh install.

Then the Langchain version can be updated periodically, any breaking changes fixed and a new Llama index version can be released, with the sureness of stability.

Langchain just had a newly published version 0.0.119. It has some breaking changes on the import path of the [BaseOutputParser](https://github.com/hwchase17/langchain/commit/ce5d97bcb3e263f6aa69da6c334e35e20bf4db11)

title: [0.5.0] Node refactor
body:
### Changes to Index construction
* main constructor now takes `nodes` instead of `documents`.
> We use `Index.from_documents` to continue support parsing documents into nodes under the hood.
* Index now holds `NodeParser` instead of `TextSplitter`
> This is a slightly higher abstraction that captures both text splitting, and setting up proper relationship between `Node`s. 

### Changes to Node class
* No longer inherit from `IndexStruct`, instead directly inherit from `BaseDocument`
> Conceptually `Node` is an extension of raw documents, and model relationship between documents (e.g.  A is source of {B, C, D}, B is a chunk before C, C is a chunk before D)
* Use `Node.relationships` to model document relationships (source, previous, next)
> This generalizes the old `ref_doc_id` and `prev_node_id`, `next_node_id`
* No longer contain relational information specific to tree index (i.e. `index` and `child_indices`)
> This is now contained in the index struct itself (e.g. `IndexGraph` in the case of `TreeIndex`)

### Changes to storage
* `Node`s are now stored in `DocumentStore` instead of as part of the `IndexStruct`
> In fact, they are added once they are created from documents. For `Index`es that create new nodes (e.g. TreeIndex), they are added to the docstore after they are created by the `Index`.

### Notes & Todos
- [x] Fix all unit test (except composability related) & lint

### Future work
- [ ] This PR draft completely ignores index composability. My hope is that it can be re-implemented cleanly in a new way. (Deferred to future PR)
- [ ] Need to implement `NodeParser` to properly setup `Node` relationships (Deferred to future PR)
- [ ] Tool for migrating old index struct jsons into new format.
- [ ] Remove or simplify `IndexRegistry`
